The paper deals with graph similarity functions and their evaluation, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories of computer science. The most likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), as the paper discusses the detection of changes in the connectivity of graphs, which is a common problem in social networks. The second likely category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), as the paper proposes a new algorithm for assessing graph similarity, which involves machine learning techniques. The third likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), as the paper discusses the scalability of the proposed algorithm and its efficiency in handling large graphs. The fourth likely category is cs.SD (Software Engineering), as the paper discusses the implementation of the proposed algorithm and its practical applications. The fifth likely category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), as the paper applies the proposed algorithm to brain connectivity graphs and uses it for classification and anomaly detection.
